**Q5: How do you correctly rethrow a wrapped exception?**

**A:** Always preserve the original exception as the 'cause':

```java
try { ... }
catch (SQLException e) {
  throw new AppException("couldn't save order", e);
  //                                             ↑ this is critical
}
```

The cause chain is what makes stack traces useful — you see the whole path from the DB failure at the bottom to your app-level error at the top. Without the cause, all you see is 'AppException: couldn't save order' — no idea *why*. `Throwable` has a constructor `(String message, Throwable cause)` for exactly this. Every custom exception should offer it.
